# Harness IaCM BVR — agent conventions

These rules apply to any agent producing or modifying a Harness IaCM Business Value Review (BVR), maturity report, growth analysis, or any customer-facing IaCM deliverable in this repo.

## Canonical structure — enforced by the renderer

Every BVR uses the **identical section ordering, naming, and chart placement** so any agent in any session produces a recognisable, brand-consistent deliverable. **The renderer enforces this**: `harness_iacm_render_report` and `harness_iacm_markdown_to_pdf` validate the markdown via `harness_iacm_bvr_validate` and **refuse to render** when the document deviates from canonical structure.

The authoritative recipe is the `iacm_bvr` MCP prompt at `src/prompts/iacm-bvr.ts`. **Always invoke that prompt** at the start of any BVR work; it returns the full instructions, chart data shapes, callout vocabulary, and frontmatter contract. Do not paraphrase from memory or invent your own section names.

The fixed top-level structure is:

```
Frontmatter (title, customer, date, defaultTheme, heroStats, bvr_template: "canonical")
Executive Summary                          [5-tile scorecard + success + critical callouts]
1. Enterprise Footprint                    [org_footprint + Top 10 Projects bar + monthly_growth]
   ### 1.1 Workspace Status Distribution   [status bar + table]
   ### 1.2 Provisioner Type & Version Sprawl [type bar + version lines bar + pin table]
2. Maturity Assessment — <tier> Tier       [maturity_radar + 9-row table + extended sprawl/registry]
3. Feature Adoption                        [4 gauges + Feature|Adoption|Note table]
   ### 3.1 Module registry standardisation [registry bar chart]
4. OPA Governance                          [opa_donut + policy-set table when sets > 0]
5. Recommended Actions                     [priority_matrix + ::: action callouts w/ Effort · +pts]
6. Before & After                          [8-row pain/gain table]
Appendix — Organisation Summary            [# org table + active projects + methodology]
Footer: Harness IaCM · BVR · <date> · <customer> · <account-url> · Confidential · live APIs
```

`harness_iacm_bvr_validate` **blocks render** if any required subsection, chart kind, or feature table is missing (not just H1 sections).

**No new top-level sections. No reordering. No renaming.** Customisations are user-driven only — never deviate pre-emptively. If the user explicitly asks for an addition (e.g. "add a Glossary section"), do that change **and** mention you've left canonical mode (set `bvr_template: "custom"` in frontmatter to satisfy the validator). If the user explicitly removes a section, same pattern.

If a section has no data (rare — typically only the growth chart if growth data isn't available), keep the heading and replace the chart with a one-line note explaining why.

### Preflight before render

After writing the markdown, call `harness_iacm_bvr_validate` with the document path. It returns:

- `valid` — boolean
- `mode` — `"canonical"` (default) or `"custom"` (escape hatch)
- `violations` — list of structural issues with line numbers
- `warnings` — soft notices (extra subsections, etc.)

Fix violations rather than skipping validation. If you absolutely need to render a non-canonical document, the only legitimate route is to either (a) the user has asked for a structural change → set `bvr_template: "custom"` in the frontmatter, or (b) it's a non-BVR document → call the renderer with `skip_validation: true`.

## Callout vocabulary — fixed, not freestyle

The renderer maps `:::` directives to specific colours. Use these exact types and only these:

| Directive | When to use |
|---|---|
| `::: success` | Strengths, "you're already doing X well" |
| `::: critical` | Largest gap or risk |
| `::: warning` | Secondary risk |
| `::: info` | Neutral context, "path to" statements |
| `::: action` | Recommended next steps (P1 / P2 / P3) |
| `::: quote` | Customer-facing quote / sales narrative |

Do not invent new directive names — they will render as plain text and look broken.

## Workspace counting — the only acceptable method

The IaCM workspace listing endpoint silently caps each page at 30 items server-side regardless of the requested `pageSize`, and returns a bare JSON array with no `total` field. Naive single-page callers undercount any project with more than 30 workspaces — historically this hid 89% of the footprint on a real customer account.

1. **Always use the shared helper** `listAllWorkspacesPaginated()` from `src/utils/iacm-pagination.ts` when listing workspaces in a project.
2. **Never trust a single-page fetch** for any number that will go into a customer report.
3. **Inspect the `_meta` block** on every scan output. `_meta.workspaceCountMethod` must be `paginated-exhaustive`. If it is anything else, the count is suspect.
4. **Treat any project reporting a suspiciously round count (30, 50, 100, etc.) as a smoke alarm** — the server cap was hit. The bundled tools paginate past this; any agent-built one-off must too.

## Provisioner version detection — the only acceptable method

The IaCM workspace **list** endpoint (`GET /iacm/api/orgs/{o}/projects/{p}/workspaces`) returns `provisioner_version: "latest"` as a summary placeholder for **every** row regardless of the workspace's real pin. The truth lives on the **GET** endpoint (`GET /iacm/api/orgs/{o}/projects/{p}/workspaces/{id}`), which returns the actual semver pin (e.g. `"1.5.7"`, `"0.13.7"`). Verified against the Autodesk tenant on 2026-05-19 — list said `latest`, GET said `1.5.7` and `1.0.11` on two adjacent workspaces.

Historically this bug caused §1.2 of a real customer BVR to claim **"100% of workspaces are unpinned to `latest`"** when the truth was **100% pinned across 9 version lines with 52% on end-of-life Terraform 0.13.x / 0.15.x** — the exact opposite finding, and one that flipped the entire P2 recommendation set.

1. **Always use `harness_iacm_workspace_inventory` with `fetch_details: true`** for §1.2 (Provisioner Type & Version Sprawl) and the Provisioner Standardisation maturity dimension. It iterates the GET endpoint internally with concurrency 12.
2. **Never derive provisioner versions from `harness_iacm_list resource_type=workspace`** — that endpoint's `provisioner_version` field is unreliable. The `provisioner` (type) and `status` fields on the list endpoint are fine; only `provisioner_version` is the placeholder bug.
3. **Smoke alarm: "100% latest."** If aggregated provisioner data shows every workspace on `latest` with zero pins, **STOP** — that is the list-endpoint bug, not a real finding. Real estates universally have at least 3-5 distinct pins. Re-derive via `workspace_inventory fetch_details: true`.
4. **If `harness_iacm_workspace_inventory` is not exposed** on the running MCP build (older builds don't ship it), the canonical fallback is `scripts/workspace-sprawl.mjs`. Run:
   ```sh
   node scripts/workspace-sprawl.mjs reports/<bvr-id>/workspace-inventory.json
   ```
   The script reads auth from `~/.cursor/mcp.json` (the `harness-iacm` entry), iterates every IaCM project, paginates each project's workspaces exhaustively, GETs every workspace by id at concurrency 12, and runs the same `classifyModuleRegistry` / `scoreVersionSprawlMaturity` aggregation that `harness_iacm_workspace_inventory` does internally. Expected runtime ~90s for ~1000 workspaces. Use the output JSON directly for §1.1, §1.2, §3.1, and the Provisioner Standardisation / Module Registry maturity dimensions. **Do not** publish list-derived provisioner versions and **do not** label them "sampled" — they are not sampled, they are wrong.
5. **The same `harness_iacm_workspace_inventory fetch_details: true` call also supplies the truthful Module Registry classification** for §3.1. The naive heuristic (just `repository` field on the list endpoint) is similarly unreliable.

## Ground-truth validation — mandatory before publishing

Before writing any markdown, generating any chart, or rendering any PDF that will be sent to a customer:

1. **Sum-and-reconcile.** Sum workspaces across orgs from the scan output → record as `A`. Compare to the IaCM dashboard total → record as `B`. If `|A - B| / B > 0.05`, **STOP** and reconcile before continuing. Common causes: timing drift during a migration ramp, or a dashboard filter the scan doesn't apply.
2. **Inspect `_meta.projectsHittingWorkspaceCap`.** This is informational once the tools paginate (we walked past the cap), but it tells you which projects have ≥30 workspaces — useful colour for the report.
3. **Inspect `_meta.unreachableProjectsForWorkspaces`.** These projects appear with workspace count `0` in the output, but that is not "no workspaces" — it is "we couldn't read them." Call this out explicitly in any report that lists them.
4. **Provisioner-version smoke test.** Before writing §1.2, glance at the version-line aggregate. If you see only one row with `provisioner_version: latest` (or one row with 100%), the list-endpoint bug bit you. See "Provisioner version detection" above and re-derive via GET.
5. **Pipelines are safe.** Pipeline counts come from the NG API's `data.totalElements` field which does not have the same bug — no special handling required.

## Methodology disclosure

Every customer-facing BVR must include the **Appendix — Organisation Summary** (per-org table with workspaces and pipelines). If the engagement requires methodology transparency (vendor reviews, audits, regulated industries), add a brief footnote under the appendix naming:

- The MCP tool used for each top-line metric (workspaces, pipelines, OPA coverage, feature adoption, growth, maturity)
- The `countMethod` from that tool's `_meta` (e.g. `paginated-exhaustive`, `totalElements`)
- Any reconciliation step performed (e.g. "Reconciled to dashboard total of 3,435 — agreed within 2.4%")

If reconciliation could not be performed (no dashboard access, no independent count path), **say so explicitly**. Do not present unreconciled numbers as if they were validated.

## Chart and asset rules

1. **Inline chart fences are the default.** Embed JSON directly in the markdown with ` ```chart <kind> ` — the renderer parses, validates via the same Zod schema as `harness_iacm_chart`, and inlines the SVG at that location. No `harness_iacm_chart` calls, no SVG files on disk, no regen step.
2. **Strict JSON inside chart fences.** Double-quoted keys, no trailing commas, no comments, no JS expressions.
3. **Never** use `harness_ccm_finops_chart` for IaCM data — only the IaCM chart kinds match the report theme.
4. **Every** number must come from a real tool response — no placeholders.

## Customer data hygiene

The `reports/` folder is gitignored by default (`reports/*` excluded, `reports/example/` opt-in). Never commit a customer-named BVR. Use `reports/example/` with anonymised data for any artifact that ships in source control.

## Tooling order for a new BVR

1. `harness_iacm_guide` — refresh on tool capabilities, validation gate, and canonical structure
2. `iacm_bvr` MCP **prompt** — pulls in the canonical BVR recipe with the exact section structure, chart shapes, callout vocabulary, and frontmatter contract for this customer engagement
3. `harness_iacm_list resource_type=harness_org` — confirm auth and visible scope
4. `harness_iacm_scan` — workspace + pipeline counts (verify `_meta.workspaceCountMethod == "paginated-exhaustive"`)
5. `harness_iacm_workspace_inventory` with **`fetch_details: true`** — **mandatory** source for provisioner/version sprawl, workspace status distribution, and module registry classification. Do **not** substitute `harness_iacm_list resource_type=workspace` for the `provisioner_version` field — that endpoint returns `"latest"` for every workspace as a placeholder regardless of the real pin (see "Provisioner version detection — the only acceptable method" above). If `workspace_inventory` is not exposed on the running MCP build, fall back to exhaustive `harness_iacm_get` per workspace and aggregate locally — **never** publish list-derived provisioner versions.
6. `harness_iacm_feature_scan` — Checkov / cost estimation / templates / private registry
7. `harness_iacm_opa_scan` — policy sets and coverage
8. `harness_iacm_growth months=12` — time-series
9. `harness_iacm_maturity_assessment` — 11-dimension scoring (includes sprawl + module registry; tiers by % of 120)
10. **Reconcile** workspace totals to dashboard ±5% before any chart or markdown
11. Write markdown using the canonical structure (see top of this rule); include status + sprawl + module registry subsections under §1 and §3 per `iacm_bvr` prompt
12. `harness_iacm_bvr_validate` — preflight the markdown before render
13. `harness_iacm_render_report` and/or `markdown_to_pdf` — produces final artifacts (these run validation again as a hard gate; if step 12 was clean, this step succeeds)
